At the same time, Trump\'92s first-day blanket pardons for more than 1,500 January 6 participants remained in force. Many of those pardoned stayed in prison on unrelated charges, but the signal was clear: political violence on behalf of the president would be forgiven. When one pardoned rioter, Andrew Taake, was arrested in Texas on pre\uc0\u8209 existing charges of soliciting a minor, it underscored that the pardon power had been used without regard to the broader criminal histories of those involved. Trump then signed an executive order directing the attorney general to produce a report on the \'93weaponization of the federal government,\'94 with findings to be routed through the White House. Attorney General Pam Bondi followed by launching a \'93Weaponization Working Group\'94 to review prosecutions of Trump and alleged abuses in January 6 cases. Together, these moves reframed independent investigations as partisan persecution and justified further purges. Law was recast as a weapon in the president\'92s hands, not a limit on his reach.\
