Bondi\'92s confirmation as attorney general was itself a key piece of the week\'92s story. The Senate approved her on a near party-line vote despite her record of anti-LGBTQ, anti-immigrant, and anti-voting-rights positions. Almost immediately, she began reshaping DOJ priorities. She dismantled the foreign bribery unit and the Kleptocracy Initiative, which had seized billions from Russian oligarchs and other corrupt actors, and narrowed the foreign bribery unit\'92s remit to drug and trafficking cases. She disbanded the FBI\'92s Foreign Influence Task Force and scaled back enforcement of white-collar crimes, including foreign bribery and money laundering. At the same time, she reinstated the federal death penalty and urged its use in certain cases. These changes weakened the government\'92s ability to police elite corruption and foreign interference while sharpening its tools against lower-level offenses, aligning enforcement with the interests of those in power. The pattern was consistent and stark.\
