The civil service, long a buffer between political whims and the daily work of government, became both target and terrain. Elon Musk, now a special government employee with a top-secret clearance, used his Department of Government Efficiency to reach deep into federal personnel systems. At the Office of Personnel Management, his associates installed an unvetted server in a conference room, bypassing procurement rules and privacy assessments, and gained broad access to databases containing medical histories, Social Security numbers, and performance evaluations for millions of employees. Senior career officials were locked out of key systems, unable to see what was being queried or changed. Musk then emailed all federal workers with a \'93deferred resignation\'94 offer, promising full pay and benefits until September 30 if they agreed to resign, while the fine print allowed agencies to require work and barred employees from enforcing the agreement in court. Unions called it a scam designed to hollow out the workforce. Roughly 20,000 employees reportedly accepted before a federal judge temporarily blocked the administration from imposing a deadline, ordering that workers be told of the delay. The message to the bureaucracy was unmistakable.\
