The most striking institutional change, however, was the removal of independent inspectors general from at least twelve major agencies. Inspectors general are the internal watchdogs who audit programs, investigate misconduct, and report to both agency heads and Congress. Firing them en masse stripped away a layer of routine oversight that had survived even earlier waves of politicization. Combined with the capture of payment systems and HR databases by DOGE, and the stacking of regulatory leadership with industry lobbyists at EPA and a fracking executive at Energy, the purge of IGs made it far easier for abuses to go undetected or unreported. Oversight was hollowed out from within.\
