Musk\'92s role in the information sphere extended beyond his social media platform. DOGE\'92s access to Treasury, CMS, SBA, Education, NOAA, and OPM systems meant that a private-led team could see, and in some cases influence, the flows of money and data that underpin public life. Treasury officials insisted that DOGE\'92s access was \'93read-only\'94 and that no valid payments had been rejected, but lawsuits by unions and OPM employees painted a different picture: servers installed without privacy reviews, senior civil servants locked out, and the practical ability to cancel transactions like the IRS Direct File program. A Wired report revealed that a 25\uc0\u8209 year\u8209 old engineer with ties to Musk\'92s companies had direct access to systems managing veterans\'92 benefits and Social Security. The administration, facing litigation, proposed to limit DOGE\'92s access to two staffers and to exclude Musk himself, but the underlying precedent\'97that a president could invite a favored billionaire into the core of the fiscal state\'97remained. Data and algorithms were being turned into tools of control.\
