On the international front, the administration moved further away from multilateral norms. Trump signed an executive order withdrawing the United States from the UN Human Rights Council and cutting funding to UNRWA, the agency serving Palestinian refugees, while ordering a review of all U.S. support to international organizations. Another order imposed sanctions on the International Criminal Court, blocking assets and visas for its officials in response to investigations of U.S. and Israeli personnel. A separate order halted U.S. aid to South Africa and prioritized resettlement of Afrikaner farmers, citing an expropriation law and echoing narratives about \'93white genocide\'94 that had circulated in right-wing media. These steps recast human-rights bodies and international courts as hostile actors to be punished, rather than forums in which the U.S. might argue its case. Foreign policy tools were bent toward a hierarchy of identity and allegiance.\
