Most dramatic was Trump\'92s public declaration, alongside Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, that the United States would \'93take over\'94 the Gaza Strip. He spoke of sending U.S. troops, resettling Palestinians elsewhere, and \'93developing\'94 Gaza as if it were a real-estate project. The proposal was welcomed by some in Israel\'92s pro-settler movement and condemned by Palestinians and neighboring states. In Washington, it drew bipartisan criticism and prompted Representative Al Green to announce articles of impeachment, calling the plan a form of ethnic cleansing. The impeachment effort was unlikely to advance in a Republican-controlled Congress, but it marked a line that some lawmakers were unwilling to see crossed. The Gaza plan, combined with threats to \'93take back\'94 the Panama Canal and to obliterate Iran, showed a foreign policy increasingly driven by personal bravado and aligned with a narrow set of allies, with little visible regard for international law or long-term stability. The risks extended far beyond rhetoric.\
