Against this backdrop, resistance did not disappear. Federal judges blocked or paused several core initiatives: the freeze on grants and loans, the coercive buyout deadline, the birthright-citizenship order, and the transfer of trans women to men\'92s prisons. FBI agents, federal employee unions, and labor groups filed lawsuits to protect privacy, jobs, and agency independence. California\'92s legislature appropriated funds to fight federal policies in court and to support immigrants. Protesters gathered at the Treasury and near the Capitol to denounce Musk\'92s influence and Trump\'92s agenda, joined by Democratic leaders who pledged to oppose what they called an assault on constitutional norms. Within the Democratic Party, new leadership emerged: Ken Martin as DNC chair and David Hogg as a vice-chair, both promising to reconnect with working-class and young voters. These actions did not stop the week\'92s structural shifts, but they showed that institutional and civic counterweights were still present and active. The struggle over the state was now out in the open.\
\
What bears watching from Week 3 is how these threads develop. Lawsuits over DOGE\'92s access to payment and personnel systems, and over the attempted dismantling of USAID, will test whether courts are willing to draw clear lines around private influence in the state. The Supreme Court\'92s consideration of the nondelegation doctrine could either preserve or sharply limit agency rulemaking, with consequences for environmental, financial, and consumer protections. Internationally, the Gaza \'93takeover\'94 rhetoric, ICC sanctions, and UN withdrawals raise questions about how far the national security bureaucracy will go in translating presidential words into plans. Domestically, the deferred-resignation scheme, the purge of inspectors general, and the stacking of regulatory posts with industry figures suggest that the shape of the administrative state itself is in play. The outcomes will determine how hard it will be to reverse what is being built now.\
